05248nam a22007215i 9789633863268DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222020hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2019011495  a9789633863268  a(DE-B1597)633440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aDR34b.B38 2020 4aDR34b.B38 2020 7aHIS0160002bisacsh04a949.6/0407222300aBattling over the Balkans :bHistoriographical Questions and Controversies /ced. by Constantin Iordachi, John R. Lampe. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (342 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tBeyond Stereotypes: Recent Trends in the Historiography on the Balkans -- tChapter 1 The Ottoman Balkans and Nation-Building -- tChapter 2 Struggling with State-Building in Interwar Yugoslavia -- tChapter 3 Irregular Violence: Bandits, Guerillas, and Militias -- tChapter 4 European Influence and Reaction: Economics and Culture -- tChapter 5 The Jews and Other Minorities during World War II -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe tumultuous history of the Balkans has been subject to a plethora of conflicting interpretations, both local and external. In an attempt to help overcome the stereotypes that still pervade Balkan history, Battling over the Balkans concentrates on a set of five principal controversies from the precommunist period with which the region’s history and historiography must contend: the pre-1914 Ottoman and Eastern Christian Orthodox legacies; the post-1918 struggles for state-building; the range of European economic and cultural influences across the interwar period, as opposed to diplomatic or political intervention; the role of violence and paramilitary forces in challenging the interwar political regimes in the region; and the fate of ethnic minorities into and after World War II, particularly Jews, Muslims and Roma. In an attempt to give a voice to eminent local authors, the chapters provide samples of new regional scholarship exploring these contested issues—most of them translated into English for the first time—and are prefaced with historiographical overviews addressing the state of the debate on these specific controversies. These translations help bridge the language barriers that often separate scholarly traditions within Southeast Europe, as well as scholars in Southeast Europe and English-speaking academia. This volume will enable readers to identify common patterns and influences that characterize the writing of history in the region, and will stimulate new transnational and comparative approaches to the history of the Balkans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  aEthnic relations, Historiography, Minorities, Ottoman Empire, South-east Europe, World Wars I & II.1 aFrusetta, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIordachi, Constantin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIordachi, Constantin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJovanović, Vladan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKechriotis, Vangelis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLampe, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLampe, John R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPavlaković, Vjeran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreshlenova, Roumiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSotiris Papaioannou, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo